Semilarski v. Prosecutor's Office: the cassation of the former Deputy Mayor Tartu will be considered on August 4
This means that the decision on it is likely to be made at the beginning of September.
The courts of the first two courts refused to consider Semilarski’s claim, but in April his cassation complaint was accepted by the State Court.
The Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant on December 12, 2019, as its authorisation is not within the jurisdiction of the Administrative Court.
The court order stated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for damage caused during the criminal proceedings.
“The prosecutor’s office and the district court should settle such issues,” Annette Kreitsmann, ERR’s press secretary for the Tartu courts, told reporters.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision in the district court, which on February 5 did not change the court's decision of the first instance.
Now the Gossud will have to say his word.
According to defender Semilarski, sworn attorney Oliver Nyas, his client about two years ago was unreasonably under suspicion of bribery.
Now he demands that the prosecutor’s office reject false allegations against him and compensate him for the moral damage.
The reason for submitting the complaint to the court was the statement of the Prosecutor on the special cases of the Lebanese District Prosecutor Margus Gross, made by him in October 2017, when Semilarski, along with another at the time Deputy Mayor Tartu Artem Suvorov, was detained on suspicion of misconduct.
“When I was detained, the Security Police and the Prosecutor’s Office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the Tartu leaders, one of the most influential bodies of local self-governments, were selling.
These air-suspended public suspicions accompanied me for about two years.
And now that these allegations and suspicions have turned out to be false, the prosecutor’s office doesn’t want to say anything about it,” Semilarski said in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Nyas, at a press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework in which the prosecutor’s office should operate.
“The claim about bribes and sales turned out to be false, but that’s not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia and Lithuania that, at the stage of the investigation, representatives of the state should be careful when choosing words so that the suspects are not represented in the role of criminals before the sentencing.
The prosecutor’s office is also bound by the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, has not been observed in this case against Valvo Semilarski,” he said.
"The public view of Semilarski as a serious offender and constable in circumstances when the facts underlying the suspicion of conspiracies are still being clarified is unacceptable, which contradicts the presumption of innocence and unfairness in relation to the statement," the statement added.
According to rus.err.ee, former deputy mayor Tartu Valvo Semilarski will not be held responsible for the charge of bribery - the criminal case against him in July was partially closed.
At the same time, the former official is being tried on charges of knowingly violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
According to the indictment, in the period from 2015 to 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu participated more than thirty times in the meetings of the city administration in making decisions related to the companies operating in Tartu, the owners or managers of which Semilarski actively communicated in private time.
According to Gross, in all these cases Semilarski had personal interests, and therefore he had to get away from participating in decision-making.
Earlier, as rus.err.ee wrote, the prosecutor’s office has presented Semilarski with suspicions of receiving bribes and violations of anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
This happened in October 2016, when he was detained along with another deputy mayor Artem Suvorov (Centrist Party).
At the time, the prosecutor’s office and the security police said there was strong evidence against both vice mayors.
After that, both officers resigned.
Suvorov’s case later came to court, which fully justified the policy.
The trial in Valvo Semilarski's case is still ongoing.
