How will the decision of the Central Bank to reduce the key rate affect the economy
The Bank of Russia is expected to reduce the key rate again.
It dropped another 0.25 percentage point to 4.25 per cent per annum, a formal historical minimum.
Judging by the return of a short rate cut, as well as the tonality of the ECB’s statements and updated forecasts on the Russian economy, the regulator looks at economic prospects more optimisticly than before.
This means that the current cycle of mitigating monetary policy could soon stop.
“We have continued to mitigate monetary policy, first of all, given that the risks of declining inflation from 4% in 2021 remain,” said Elvira Nabiullin, head of the Bank of Russia.
They are associated with a significant decrease in economic activity, a fall in domestic and external demand.
The restoration of the economy, according to Nabiullina, will take more than a year and a half.
At the same time, she noted that after the lifting of restrictions due to the pandemic, economic processes revived: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand were restored, the construction and production of consumer goods were expanded, the annual rates of reduction in the turnover of transport, transport and transport were slowed.
According to the Central Bank’s detailed forecast, in 2020 the economy will be reduced by 4.5-5.5% (previously expected by 4-6%), and the recovery growth of the economy in 2021 will be 3.5-4.5%, in 2022 - 2.5-3.5%.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised the forecast for annual oil prices to $38 and $40 per barrel of Urals in 2020 and 2021, respectively.
Previously, the Central Bank expected $27 and $35 per barrel.
Finally, the forecast of the Bank of Russia on inflation for 2020 was 3.7-4.2% versus previously expected 3.8-4.8%.
The view of the Bank of Russia on the situation in the economy is becoming more optimistic, which brings us closer to the end of the cycle of mitigation, economists in Russia and the CIS "Renaissance Capital" Sofia Donets and Andrey Melashchenko believe.
Thus, the Bank of Russia has consistently reduced the key rate for more than a year, since the beginning of last summer it has already fallen by 3.5 percentage points.
And at the last meeting in June, the Central Bank lowered it to one percentage point immediately because of the low rates of inflation due to the depressed demand and the need to stimulate the slowdown due to the pandemic and its related economic constraints.
Chances for the adjustment of monetary policy remain (at the next meeting on September 18 and until the end of the year), but the limit is already close, agreed the chief analyst of Rosbank Evgeny Koshelev.
The set of pro-inflation risks also points to the nearness of the pause in mitigating interest rate policies – broken supply chains, possible cost growth due to epidemic prevention measures and faster (compared to expectations) recovery of demand, he says.
In order to complete the subsequent actions of the Bank of Russia will require more attention to the inflation processes during the harvest season, as well as external volatility, which has increased against the background of geopolitical conflicts, Koshelev points out.
One way or another, the reduction of the key rate will lead to a further reduction in rates for the most reliable borrowers, as well as, perhaps, on the mortgage, says senior economist of the analytical management of the bank "Opening" Maxim Petronevich.
The rate adjustment will be less pronounced than the reduction of the key rate, he said.
Interest rates on receivables may fall by an additional 0.3-0.6 percentage points during the second half of the year, mortgage rates may end a year in the range of 6.2-7%, does not exclude the economist "BKS Primer" Anton Pokatovich.
The average rates of contributions, according to him, will also fall - in the coming months they can fall to 4.2-4.5% (now just above 4.5%).
They can then go down to 4% if the central bank lowers its key rate in the fall, Pokatovich said.
