The actor of the Russian series responded to the accusations in the "propaganda of LGBT and feminism"
The actor of the Russian series "Chicago", whose creators were accused of "propaganda of LGBT and feminism", responded to the claim to the film.
The authors "understood the sharpness of the themes raised and didn't want to offend anyone," said American Stephen Thomas Oxner in an interview with Rise.
“I think it’s a story about strength and the general aspects of human life.
It has nothing to do with LGBT and feminism,” said the actor, who played the father of the boy, who changed into women’s clothing.
He said he was "proud about the job" and did not consider it to be propaganda.
At the same time, the American added, he is afraid of the reaction of some people to the storyline of the series: for example, there was a case where "a man in a deep trance shot the shooting platform and said it was all untrue."
“Then there were a couple of cases when we met disgruntled locals who didn’t understand what we were doing.
But we were open, so the people who came with the claims first started to help us," he said.
The shooting, according to the publication, occurred in September 2019 in Kabardino-Balkaria: a drunk man attacked the car of a shooting group with weapons, after which he was detained by police officers.
